city and silent protest to pressure Marriott International. Marriott set a new target to source only cage-free eggs globally by 2025, reiterating its commitment to eliminating caged eggs from its global supply chain. In 2024, Marriott reported that 42.04% of the eggs in its supply chain were cage-free.\n\nIn May 2025, the animal protection nonprofit Mercy For Animals claimed Marriott has attempted to silence activists. According to Mercy For Animals CEO Leah Garcés, the company sought to take down campaign websites that shared updates on its cage-free progress.\n\nDuring a June 2025 hotel industry conference at the New York Marriott Marquis, a protest concerning the use of eggs from caged hens interrupted a panel featuring executives from major hotel companies, including Marriott International.\n\nAccording to The Washington Post, as of 2026, Marriott International has not fulfilled this commitment. As of January 2026, Marriott International has declined to provide updated timelines for its global cage-free egg commitment, citing bird flu and supply chain disruptions as obstacles to the 2025 deadline.","logoUrl":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Marriott_International_Headquarters_01.jpg/330px-Marriott_International_Headquarters_01.jpg","wikipediaUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marriott_International","extract":"Marriott International, Inc. is an American multinational company that operates, franchises, and licenses lodging brands that include hotel, residential, and timeshare properties. The company owns over 37 hotel and timeshare brands, with 9,000 locations and 1,597,380 rooms across its network. Headquartered in Bethesda, Maryland, the company is the successor to the hospitality division of the Marriott Corporation, which was founded by J. Willard Marriott (1900–1985) and his wife Alice Marriott (1907–2000)."},"logoUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Marriott%20International.svg","logoSource":"wikidata_p154","s